Maybe it's time to have this thread split, no? Anyway, let's go! =)<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Famiclones tend to fail Blargg's tests and have screwed up pulse waves.<br /></div><br />I don't think Joe Gamer cares about that. And although there are a few games that have trouble running on famiclones, I doubt that modern developers will make abuse of timing tricks, as it's hardly necessary in a real game. In demos, yes sure, it's fun, but in games, I just don't see the need. There are hardly any complex finished games, so I don't see any that use tricky timing in the near future. IMO, it would be a while before this becomes a serious issue.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />In the United States, where can I order an accurate famiclone that doesn't come packed with a pirate multicart?<br /></div><br />If you hate the pirate cart that much, just don't play it. Burn it if it makes you happy. You are taking this piracy thing to an extreme, man. Relax. And I'm sure there are quality famiclones that don't come with any carts (my pokefami, for example, didn't have one). Also, a while back, you said that famiclones can have unresponsive controls, but there are quite a few out there that are pretty good (the pokefami is not particularly good here, but it accepts external controllers).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />1. rare, and 2. no AV output. The common case by far is the front-loader.<br /></div><br />I know the front-loader is way more common, but I'm saying that there is an option (and it's <strong>legal</strong>, which I know scores major points with you). And I believe there are converters that will split RF into audio and video. I know it won't make quality better, but will make the NES more compatible.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />A lot of morons are afraid of breaking their NES or the law.<br /></div><br />As I said, Joe Gamer could be very happy with his famiclone. People who are serious about this should be able to cut a pin. And you can't be serious about this "breaking the law" thing. I find it really nice that you like to do things the right way, buy only legal stuff and all, I really do. If I lived in the US, where prices are way more fair and things are way more organized than here in Brazil (when things get here, they cost double the price it costs for you guys), I'm sure I'd be like that too. But it's just a small freaking tiny piece of metal, inside of something that you <strong>own</strong>. You have the right to do whatever you want with it, as long as it doesn't hurt Nintendo. I doubt any "lockout chip pin inspector" will ever knock on my door!<br /><br />I just don't think it's fair to blame it all on the lockout chip. As Bregalad said, the japanese don't have it, and the scene is still pretty slow over there too. The japanese MSX scene is incredibly more active.<br /><br />I'm not acusing anyone of anything either. I'm the first to not finish anything I start. Most of you have done much more than I have. I'm just wishing here, you know?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Fri Oct 20, 2006 7:59 pm</p><hr />
